1. gcloud auth list
    gcloud auth list displays all Google Cloud accounts that are currently authenticated on your local machine and shows which account is active. who am I?
    In simple terms: It tells you who is logged in to the gcloud CLI. it allows you to Check active account
    🔹 Switch Active Account, If you have multiple accounts and want to switch:
        gcloud config set account admin@company.com

🔹 Related Commands (Very Useful)
    ✅ Login to a new account:  gcloud auth login
    ✅ Activate service account (for automation):  gcloud auth activate-service-account --key-file=service-account-key.json
    ✅ Remove an account: gcloud auth revoke user@example.com

  In GCP, authentication (account) and configuration (project) are separate. After checking accounts, also check project: gcloud config list project
  Set project if needed: gcloud config set project my-project-id

  🔹 Real‑World Scenario: You run a deployment command and get a permission error. First thing to check: gcloud auth list
        ✅ Maybe the wrong account is active
        ✅ Switch to the correct one and retry

    🔹 Common Mistakes ❌
❌ Assuming the last logged‑in account is active
❌ Forgetting to switch accounts before production work
❌ Confusing project permissions with authentication

2. gcloud config list project
    gcloud config list project displays the Google Cloud project that is currently set as active in your local gcloud CLI configuration. in short it allows you to 
    check active project. where am I working
    If the project is missing or incorrect:  gcloud config set project new-project-id
    🔹 Override Project Temporarily (Per Command): Instead of changing global config, you can do:        gcloud compute instances list --project=some-other-project
        ✅ Useful in scripts or multi‑project environments

    🔹 Real‑World Scenario: You run a deploy command and it fails or deploys to the wrong environment.
        First checks:   gcloud auth list
                        gcloud config list project

   ✅ List all configs:      gcloud config list


3. User Accounts vs Service Accounts (GCP)
    🔹 High‑Level Difference: User accounts are for humans interacting with GCP, while service accounts are for applications and automated processes.
    🔹 What is a Service Account? A service account is a non‑human identity used by: Applications, Virtual machines, CI/CD pipelines, Kubernetes workloads
        Example: my-service@my-project.iam.gserviceaccount.com
     Service accounts are used when: A VM accesses Cloud Storage, A Kubernetes Pod accesses Pub/Sub, A CI/CD pipeline deploys to GCP, A backend talks to another GCP service.
    ✅ Authentication (Service Account): gcloud auth activate-service-account --key-file=service-account-key.json 
        or recommended (no keys): Attached automatically to: Compute Engine, GKE, Cloud Run, App Engine.
    ✅ Why Service Accounts Are Safer: ✔ No passwords, ✔ Scoped permissions, ✔ Can be rotated, ✔ Fully auditable, ✔ Principle of least privilege.
      

